lrn_hiVar_2.comments: It was clear from the beginning each colour corresponded to a relatively similar structure of the final segment of the word, and that each symbol corresponded to an equal initial segment. However, the text-to-speech modulator used in this study was incredibly subpar. The TTS actively harmed learning new words, because it pronounced each colour variation almost exactly the same. I do not know if that was the intent of the study or a side effect, but I found it easier to memorize if I tried to actively ignore the voice.

I noticed some colors (for example gray) having the -koh ending. I then tried to remember the others. I did not take any notes. I repeated each word after hearing it, or read them out loud while being seeing them.

If I knew I was allowed to take notes, I would have! I noticed a consistent pattern in the name of the shapes (beginning of the word) and a pattern in the color (end of the word) but with some exceptions for the colors, it seemed. Also sometimes consonants in the middle of the word were doubled and sometimes they were not. It took me some time to realize I also had to take into account the color of the object (at first I thought only the shape mattered). The difficult aspect of the task was the exceptions and the fact that everything was going very fast. I didn't have enough time to properly see the correction made to my answers and to pause, think, and make sense of it all.

Strategy: 1.Find similarities in word structure, i.e. first half of word for shape, second half of word for color.  2.Look for irregularities (yellow star: gaffychoe with two 'f')

It was easy overall!
